### 1. Only consecutive chosen indices matter

Suppose the chosen indices are
$$p_1<p_2<\dots<p_k.$$

Assume every consecutive pair is valid. Consider any nonconsecutive pair $p_r<p_s$.

Because $p_{r+1}$ lies between them,
$$p_s-p_r>p_{r+1}-p_r>a_{p_r}.$$

Similarly, using the last gap before $p_s$,
$$p_s-p_r>p_s-p_{s-1}>a_{p_s}.$$

Therefore
$$p_s-p_r>\max(a_{p_r},a_{p_s}),$$
so that pair is valid too. Thus it is enough to ensure compatibility between consecutive selected assignments.

That turns the problem into finding a maximum-weight path through indices from left to right.

### 2. The DP transition

Define $dp[j]$ as the maximum total weight of a valid selection whose rightmost chosen assignment is $j$.

If $i<j$ is the previous chosen index, compatibility requires
$$j-i>\max(a_i,a_j).$$

This is equivalent to satisfying both
$$j-i>a_i$$
and
$$j-i>a_j.$$

Rearranging them gives
$$i+a_i<j$$
and
$$i<j-a_j.$$

Since all values are integers, the second inequality becomes
$$i\le j-a_j-1.$$

Hence
$$dp[j]=a_j+\max_{\substack{i+a_i<j\\i\le j-a_j-1}}dp[i].$$

If no such $i$ exists, the best selection ending at $j$ contains only $j$, so $dp[j]=a_j$.

A quadratic implementation would inspect every earlier $i$. That is obviously dead on arrival for $n=2\cdot10^5$, so we need to separate the two restrictions.

### 3. Activating usable previous indices

Sweep $j$ from left to right.

The restriction
$$i+a_i<j$$
becomes permanently true starting at
$$j=i+a_i+1.$$

Call $i$ **active** from that time onward. When computing $dp[i]$, we schedule index $i$ to be activated at time $i+a_i+1$. If this time is larger than $n$, it can never be used by any later assignment and does not need to be scheduled.

At the start of step $j$, every active index already satisfies the first transition restriction. Among those indices, we still need the maximum $dp[i]$ with
$$i\le j-a_j-1.$$

That is a prefix-maximum query by index.

### 4. Fenwick tree for prefix maximums

A Fenwick tree is usually introduced for sums, but its update/query structure works just as well for monotone maximums:

- `update(i, value)` records that position $i$ has value `value`;
- `query(r)` returns the maximum value among positions $1$ through $r$.

We never remove active indices, so maximum updates are perfect here.

For each position $j$:

1. Insert every index whose activation time is exactly $j$ into the Fenwick tree using its already-computed $dp$ value.
2. Compute
   $$r=j-a_j-1.$$
3. Query the maximum active $dp[i]$ over $i\le r$.
4. Set
   $$dp[j]=a_j+\text{query}(r).$$
5. Schedule $j$ for activation at $j+a_j+1$, if that time is at most $n$.

A query with $r\le0$ simply returns $0$, representing starting a new selection at $j$.

### 5. Why the algorithm is correct

We prove by induction over $j$ that $dp[j]$ is the best score of any valid selection ending at $j$.

For a selection containing only $j$, the score is $a_j$, which the transition can always produce because the empty-prefix value is $0$.

Now consider a valid selection ending at $j$ with some previous chosen index $i$. Since $i$ and $j$ are consecutive in that selection, they must satisfy $i+a_i<j$ and $i\le j-a_j-1$. Therefore $i$ is active when step $j$ begins and lies inside the queried Fenwick prefix. By the induction hypothesis, $dp[i]$ is the best score ending at $i$, so the algorithm considers a score at least as large as this selection's prefix plus $a_j$.

Conversely, every index returned by the query is active, hence satisfies $i+a_i<j$, and is inside the queried prefix, hence satisfies $i\le j-a_j-1$. Thus $i$ and $j$ are compatible. Appending $j$ to an optimal selection ending at $i$ creates a valid selection, because checking consecutive chosen indices is sufficient.

So the transition considers exactly all valid possibilities, and $dp[j]$ is correct. The final answer is
$$\max_{1\le j\le n}dp[j],$$
with $0$ also implicitly allowed for the empty subset.

### Complexity

Each index is inserted into the Fenwick tree at most once and causes one prefix query.

- Time: $O(n\log n)$ per test case
- Memory: $O(n)$

Across all test cases, the total $n$ is at most $2\cdot10^5$.","solution":"#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

using ll = long long;

void setIO() {
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);
}

struct FenwickMax {
    int n;
    vector<ll> bit;

    FenwickMax(int n) : n(n), bit(n + 1, 0) {}

    void update(int i, ll value) {
        for (; i <= n; i += i & -i)
            bit[i] = max(bit[i], value);
    }

    ll query(int i) const {
        ll result = 0;
        for (; i > 0; i -= i & -i)
            result = max(result, bit[i]);
        return result;
    }
};

int main() {
    setIO();

    int t;
    cin >> t;
    while (t--) {
        int n;
        cin >> n;

        vector<ll> a(n + 1), dp(n + 1);
        for (int i = 1; i <= n; ++i)
            cin >> a[i];

        vector<vector<int>> activate(n + 1);
        FenwickMax fw(n);
        ll answer = 0;

        for (int j = 1; j <= n; ++j) {
            for (int i : activate[j])
                fw.update(i, dp[i]);

            ll bound = (ll)j - a[j] - 1;
            ll best = fw.query(bound > 0 ? (int)bound : 0);
            dp[j] = best + a[j];
            answer = max(answer, dp[j]);

            ll when = (ll)j + a[j] + 1;
            if (when <= n)
                activate[(int)when].push_back(j);
        }

        cout << answer << '\n';
    }
}"}

